{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 19:06:24.095502", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — Clos EBGP lab\nSummary\n- Overall control-plane (FRR/BGP) appears converged across routers (super-spine, spine, leaves). BGP tables show the expected /24 host subnets propagated and many inter-router /31 links present.\n- Data-plane anomaly limited to host pc_0_0: the host has no L2/L3 address configured and is not participating on its access link. As a result pc_0_0 is unreachable from the rest of the fabric. Other hosts (example pc_0_1) are reachable and exchanging traffic normally.\n\nScope / impact\n- Affected: pc_0_0 (host). It cannot reach or be reached by other hosts in the test; reachability checks for pc_0_0 returned unknown.\n- Unaffected: control plane (BGP) and the rest of hosts shown (pc_0_1 and other PCs) — they show successful pings and the routers carry full routes for all /24s.\n\nKey evidence and observations\n1) Reachability scan (summary)\n- get_reachability output shows pc_0_1 entries as OK and many other PCs reachable. pc_0_0 entries were reported as \"unknown\" (no ping results), indicating lack of connectivity from or to pc_0_0.\n\n2) pc_0_0 network configuration (host-local)\n- Output for pc_0_0:\n  - ifconfig/ip addr: only loopback present; no eth0 or other host interface with an IP.\n  - ip route: empty.\n  -> This indicates the host has no IP configured and/or its interface is down or missing.\n\n3) pc_0_1 network configuration (comparison)\n- pc_0_1: eth0 configured with 10.0.1.2/24 and default via 10.0.1.1; ifconfig and route look normal. Reachability tests from many sources to pc_0_1 succeeded, confirming fabric forward/return behavior for other hosts is working.\n\n4) Leaf and spine BGP and routing state (control-plane)\n- leaf_router_0_0 BGP / routing: shows 10.0.0.0/24 as directly connected (C>* 10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, eth8) and many 172.16.1.x /31 interfaces present and BGP routes for other /24s. The routing table entries and BGP tables across leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1 and super_spine_router_0 indicate routes for the entire addressing scheme are present and propagated.\n- Multiple routers show each /24 learned via expected EBGP next-hops; the super-spine has routes for the 10.1.x networks via the expected paths. There is no obvious sign of BGP session flaps or missing prefixes in the provided router outputs.\n\nLocalization of the fault\n- Layer 1/2/3 problem is localized to the host side of the (leaf_router_0_0 <-> pc_0_0) link:\n  - The leaf router (leaf_router_0_0) believes the 10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected on an interface (eth8), but the host (pc_0_0) has no interface address or routes configured.\n  - The absence of an IP/interface on pc_0_0 explains the \"unknown\" reachability status for that host while routers and other hosts remain functional.\n\nProbable root cause\n- Primary root cause: pc_0_0 is not configured/up on its network interface (no eth0 address present). This could be due to one of:\n  - Host NIC down or administratively disabled;\n  - Host network configuration missing (no IP assigned);\n  - Host interface not present / driver issue;\n  - Physical cable/link between the host and leaf down (less likely given the leaf reports the subnet as directly connected, but possible that the leaf interface is up even if the host link is down).\n- There is no evidence in the collected data of BGP/control-plane failure or routing convergence issues affecting other subnets — the problem is host-local.\n\nAdditional notes / uncertainties\n- The leaf advertises 10.0.0.0/24 as connected. If the leaf is configured to advertise that subnet even when no host is present, the fabric will show the subnet as reachable from a routing perspective — but the host will remain unreachable. The data collected does not show ARP behavior on the leaf or L2 status from the leaf toward the host; that would confirm whether the physical link is up.\n- I did not observe BGP session down messages or missing prefixes for other networks in the provided router outputs; however, the router logs and interface state (eth counters, ARP tables) on leaf_router_0_0 were not collected — those would help to confirm whether the leaf sees/link-level connectivity to the host.\n\nConclusions\n- Network control-plane (FRR/BGP) is healthy and routes are converged.\n- The single clear anomaly is that pc_0_0 has no network interface/address configured and is therefore not participating in the data-plane. The issue is localized to pc_0_0 (host side) or, less likely, the immediate access link between pc_0_0 and leaf_router_0_0.\n- No other routers or hosts show anomalies in the data gathered.\n\nIf you want, I can run additional targeted checks to further narrow whether the link is physical (e.g., inspect leaf_router_0_0 interface state, ARP table, or run an ARP ping) — but I will not provide remediation steps unless you request them.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 25607, "output_tokens": 2352, "total_tokens": 27959, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 8832}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1152}}}
